x4freetext: Neutron production target at GELINA
GELINA, 150MeV Geel pulsed electron
linac, electron burst width 1 ns, repetition rate
800 Hz, average electron current 70 microA, average
electron energy 100 MeV.
Neutrons produced by (g,n) and (g,f)
reactions induced via Bremsstrahlung from the
electron beam hitting a mercury cooled rotating
uranium target.
Moderation of the neutrons in water filled
Be-containers located above uranium target results in
a white neutron spectrum.
GELINA flight path number 13; angle of the
flight path with respect to the electron beam is
108 deg.
The alpha-particles were detected using a
Frisch-gridded ionization chamber filled with
ultra pure C-H4 as detector gas.
BF3 proportional counters were located at
different places above the neutron source. Their
output is used to normalize spectra to the same total
neutron flux.
The neutron flux is
determined based on the well-known reaction using
a B-10 sample in an ionization chamber. The data
from ENDF/B-VI are used.
.Evaporated elemental boron (7.17+-0.13)E+19 atoms
.Background corrections for flux and capture:
* based on Au, Co, Mn, Rh and W black resonances
* deduced from a fit - using AGS - of the background
points with a function like: BG(TOF)=a*TOF**b+c,
with a,b and c adjustable parameters and TOF
the neutron time-of-flight.
total uncertainties were deduced by propagating
correlated and uncorrelated partial uncertainties
using AGS; details in main reference
Partial uncertainties considered were due to:
* counting statistics
* uncertainties on number of atoms in the 10B and
36Cl samples
* correction for the time dependent background
LdS/HH/SM
Last corrections have been done
Corrections made. SM
Corrections made in SAN 003. SM
On. TITLE corrected
Only the first resonance
at 931 keV has a significant alpha contribution of
(76 +/- 7)%. All the other resonances are regarded
as proton resonances with a negligible alpha
contribution.
.Silver chloride on a platinum coated aluminium foil,
effective area = 6 * 5 cm2, 36Cl enrichment = 40.50%,
thickness = 4.63E17 Cl-36 atoms/cm**2
placed at 30.39 m from the neutron source
.The neutron energy is derived from the measured
time-of-flight using En(eV)=(72.298*L/TOF)**2 with
L = 8.48 m and TOF in microseconds
.White initial neutron source. Cd overlap filter kept
permanently in the neutron beam
for 17 resonances. Spin and total level widths are
calculated for 5 resonances. Results are in good
agreement with previous data but the resolution is
better.
.Using the obtained cross section data, Maxwellian
Averaged Cross Sections were calculated and compared
with other experimental and theoretical values.
They are used in stellar model calculations.
<<By the authors: The meaning of the quantities in the
DATA section is:
EN     (eV)   - neutron energy, low bound of zone
DATA   (barn) - (N,P)+(N,A) partial cross section
ERR    (barn) - total uncertainty
.Negative data values occur occasionally as a result
of the background corrections. These values are
consistent with zero within the experimental
uncertainty.  >>
